Analysis of the World Covid-19 Dataset

The world-of-data website hosts world-wide epidemiological data on the Corona Virus (COVID-19). The dataset is compiled by the Johns Hopkins University Center for Systems Science and Engineering (JHU CCSE) from various sources, and follows The dataset contains data since January 2020. For the data and more information about it, please visit here.

You can see several nice visualizations of the data here

we will focus on analyzing the Covid-19 cases, deaths and vaccinations data over time for different countries and continents.

  8. Cross correlations and delay from diagnosis to death: We want to use the data and cross-correlation in order to study the typical time delay between diagnosis of Covid-19 and death from Covid-19 for cases not surviving the disease. For two functions of time \(X(t)\) and \(Y(t)\) (here \(t\) is discrete, representing for example days) we define their cross-correlation at time-delay \(\Delta_t\) as follows: \(cross_{corr}(\Delta_t ; X, Y) = Corr(X(t), Y(t+\Delta_t))\).
    That is, the cross-correlation function at the time-delay \(\Delta_t\) for two vectors of length \(n\) is obtained by computing the Pearson correlation coefficient of the vector \(X[1,...,n-\Delta_t]\) with the vector \(Y[\Delta_t+1,...,n]\), for \(\Delta_t>0\). For \(\Delta_t < 0\) we replace the role of \(X\) and \(Y\) in this formula.

    1. Write a function that receives as input the data-frame, a country name and the name of two columns, and computes the value of their cross-correlation in this country for time delay of up to two months apart, that is for all values of \(\Delta_t\) between \(-60\) days and \(60\) days. The function should return a vector of length \(121\) representing these correlations. Do not use available cross-correlation functions in \(R\), but write the function yourself.

    2. Use the function from (a.) to compute the cross correlation between the number of new_cases_smoothed and new_deaths_smoothed for the entire World, and plot it as a function of \(\Delta_t\).   1. In the second question we were requested to create a comparison function and use it on diffrenet varibles in order to analyze differences between high and low income countries. We started this question by writing the requested function: a function that compares between the high income countries and the low income countries by visualaizing the diffrences in a given variable using a plot:
  compare <- function(df,col_name){
  df_sorted <- subset(df, location == c("High income", "Low income"), is.na(date) == FALSE
  , is.na(col_name) == FALSE)       # creating new data frame which contains only the rows with "low income" or "high income" as their location.
  ggplot1 <- ggplot(data = df_sorted, aes_string(y=col_name, x="date",
  colour = "location", group = "location")) + geom_line() + xlab("date") + 
  ylab(col_name)      # creating the plot which visualizing the diffrences.
  return (ggplot1)
}

We then used the function we created in a, to compare diffrenet variables:

#Calculating booster ratio
for(i in 1:length(df$total_boosters)){
  if(is.na(df$total_boosters[i] || is.na(df$people_fully_vaccinated[i]) || df$people_fully_vaccinated==0)){
    df$booster_ratio=NA
  }
  else{
    df$booster_ratio = df$total_boosters/df$people_fully_vaccinated
  }
}

We are requested to calculate the R_cases, which represent the rate in which the pandemic spreads, and analyze it through a graph of Israel, the united Kingdom, and then United States

#Here we calculate the R_cases
for(i in 1:length(df$date)){
  if (i<=7 || df$new_cases_smoothed[i-7] ==0 || is.na(df$new_cases_smoothed[i-7])){
    df$R_cases[i] = NA
  }
  else{
    df$R_cases[i] = df$new_cases_smoothed[i]/df$new_cases_smoothed[i-7]
  }
}

  1. In this question we were required to recreate the “CCF” function without using it and run it on the “new_cases_smoothed” and “new_deaths_smoothed” variables. We first recreated the cross_corr function:
cross_corr <- function(given_df, country, col1, col2){
  given_df=subset(given_df,location == country )   #keeping infomartion only about the given country
  given_df[is.na(given_df)]<-0        # making sure there aren't any na values.
  col1_vec<-as.numeric(as.list(t(given_df[,col1])))  
  col2_vec<-as.numeric(as.list(t(given_df[,col2])))
  res_vec=vector(length=121)    #creating the result vector
  for (i in 1:60){         #calculating the correletions of the given vectors, each time using diffrenet indexes over the period of 120 days:
    res_vec[i+61]= cor(col1_vec[1:(length(col1_vec)-i)], col2_vec[(i+1):length(col2_vec)], use="complete.obs")
    res_vec[61-i]= cor(col1_vec[(i+1):length(col1_vec)], col2_vec[1:(length(col2_vec)-i)], use="complete.obs")
  }
  res_vec[60]= cor(given_df[,col1], given_df[,col2], use = "complete.obs")    #  adding the 60th index in the result vector
  return(res_vec)
}

Then we ran the function we built in a on the “new_cases_smoothed” and “new_deaths_smoothed” variables and plotted the resulted vector of values as a function of delta(going from -60 to 60):

corr_newcases_newdeaths<-cross_corr(df, "World", "new_cases_smoothed", "new_deaths_smoothed")
del<-(-60:60)
plot(del,corr_newcases_newdeaths)

By looking at the plot and the result vector of the two variables we can see that the maximized value of the cross correlation is given when delta=13. From this, we can conclude that the 13th day after getting diagnosed positive with “Covid”, is the day which most death casualties occur in, in other words, it’s the day with the most probability to die from the Corona virus.
